    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "A weather analyst wants to compare consecutive temperature readings between different cities for each day. They will analyze consecutive pairs of temperatures in column-major order to determine temperature trends.\r\n\r\n<pre style=\"background-color: #333333; color: white;\"> Row 1: 37.27, 40.66, 53.53, 52.36, 48.87 (New York) Row 2: 62.2, 61.47, 60.31, 62.42, 62.38 (Los Angeles) Row 3: 81.5, 80.04, 81.61, 85.91, 85.69 (Miami) Row 4: 56.41, 48.6, 51.67, 48.72, 52.65 (Seattle) </pre>\r\nEach row represents a city (New York, Los Angeles, Miami, Seattle), and each column represents a date (March 29th – April 2nd).\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #1:** In the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">Temperatures</code> class, write the method <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">compareConsecutiveCities()</code> to compare consecutive city temperatures for each day.\r\n\r\n1. Loop through each column (day).\r\n2. Compare consecutive pairs of cities (rows in the same column).\r\n3. Determine if the second city's temperature is higher or lower than the first.\r\n4. Return a String containing comparisons for each day.\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #2:** In the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">TemperaturesRunner</code> class, call the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black;\">compareConsecutiveCities()</code> method and print the result.\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #E0D1EC; border: 1px solid #9660bf; border-radius: 5px; font-size: 1.1em; padding: 15px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">\r\n💡 <strong>TIP:</strong> Check out the <strong>Help & Tips</strong> tab ⬆️ for help with traversing a two-dimensional (2D) array in column-major order.\r\n</div>",
